+/// Whether equality of a value of type `ty` must be compiled field-wise
+/// because the type is a struct that transitively contains a `Float` (B28 P3
+/// item 5, Phase A).
+///
+/// A float-bearing struct is flat (Phase B); a raw-byte `CmpEq` over its body
+/// would diverge from IEEE on `+0.0`/`-0.0` (equal values, distinct bytes)
+/// and `NaN` (equal bytes, unequal values), so the compiler emits a per-field
+/// comparison instead. A bare `Float` scalar is already IEEE-correct under
+/// `CmpEq`; tuples, arrays, and enums keep boxing their floats this iteration
+/// (their derived comparison is IEEE-correct, and flattening them is a
+/// documented follow-up); and a type the layout pass cannot resolve falls
+/// back to `CmpEq` (it was not flattened either, so the boxed comparison is
+/// correct).
+///
+/// Residual limitation: a float-bearing struct whose operand type the
+/// compiler cannot infer at the comparison site falls back to `CmpEq` and
+/// would compare its flat body by bytes. This mirrors the existing
+/// inference-dependent flat-access baking; consuming the type checker's
+/// authoritative annotations would close it.
